snippet.textDisplay:
I don't know why caskets are blocky now, but if I had to guess, I'd say probably because of eastern influence?

My Italian great grandma passed away a couple of years back and as it turns out, unlike in Poland, most graveyards have a lot of vertical space instead of a lot of ground to bury people in. And the "cells" of those vertical burial spots are very much square.

It's just a guess tho ¯\_(ツ)_/¯ America is christian and not catholic so this might be completely off, but I'd say catholic influence, especially when it comes to money, might be to blame

snippet.textDisplay:
Since we're talking about death and the afterlife here's my opinion to help your existential crisis!

Life nor death is not forever. Time is infinite and always moving, so even though that person is dead in your time, they're alive in another. Right now time is moving through their happiest memories and they're experiencing that again and for the first time! Its like when you read a book; even though the series is finished you can go back to book one and it happens all over again. When a book is finished you can always re read it. So even though that physical person isin't there, somewhere out there they're being.

Hope this helped or contributed to your crisis :)
